{
  "$schema": "https://json.schemastore.org/sarif-2.1.0.json",
  "version": "2.1.0",
  "runs": [
    {
      "tool": {
        "driver": {
          "name": "PMD",
          "version": "7.22.0",
          "informationUri": "https://docs.pmd-code.org/latest/",
          "rules": [
            {
              "id": "CommentSize",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Comment is too large: Line too long"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "\nDetermines whether the dimensions of non-header comments found are within the specified limits.\n        "
              },
              "helpUri": "https://docs.pmd-code.org/snapshot/pmd_rules_java_documentation.html#commentsize",
              "help": {
                "text": "\nDetermines whether the dimensions of non-header comments found are within the specified limits.\n        "
              },
              "properties": {
                "ruleset": "Documentation",
                "priority": 3,
                "tags": [
                  "Documentation"
                ]
              },
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "warning"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "AtLeastOneConstructor",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Each class should declare at least one constructor"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "\n\nEach non-static class should declare at least one constructor.\nClasses with solely static members are ignored, refer to [UseUtilityClassRule](pmd_rules_java_design.html#useutilityclass) to detect those.\n\n        "
              },
              "helpUri": "https://docs.pmd-code.org/snapshot/pmd_rules_java_codestyle.html#atleastoneconstructor",
              "help": {
                "text": "\n\nEach non-static class should declare at least one constructor.\nClasses with solely static members are ignored, refer to [UseUtilityClassRule](pmd_rules_java_design.html#useutilityclass) to detect those.\n\n        "
              },
              "properties": {
                "ruleset": "Code Style",
                "priority": 3,
                "tags": [
                  "Code Style"
                ]
              },
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "warning"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "LongVariable",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Avoid excessively long variable names like ETC_ALTERNATIVES_X_TERMINAL_EMULATOR"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "\nFields, formal arguments, or local variable names that are too long can make the code difficult to follow.\n        "
              },
              "helpUri": "https://docs.pmd-code.org/snapshot/pmd_rules_java_codestyle.html#longvariable",
              "help": {
                "text": "\nFields, formal arguments, or local variable names that are too long can make the code difficult to follow.\n        "
              },
              "properties": {
                "ruleset": "Code Style",
                "priority": 3,
                "tags": [
                  "Code Style"
                ]
              },
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "warning"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CommentRequired",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Field comments are required"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "\nDenotes whether javadoc (formal) comments are required (or unwanted) for specific language elements.\n        "
              },
              "helpUri": "https://docs.pmd-code.org/snapshot/pmd_rules_java_documentation.html#commentrequired",
              "help": {
                "text": "\nDenotes whether javadoc (formal) comments are required (or unwanted) for specific language elements.\n        "
              },
              "properties": {
                "ruleset": "Documentation",
                "priority": 3,
                "tags": [
                  "Documentation"
                ]
              },
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "warning"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "MethodArgumentCouldBeFinal",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Parameter 'filePath' is not assigned and could be declared final"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "\n            Reports method and constructor parameters that can be made final because they are never reassigned within the body of the method.\n\n            This rule ignores unused parameters so as not to overlap with the rule {% rule java/bestpractices/UnusedFormalParameter %}.\n            It will also ignore the parameters of abstract methods.\n        "
              },
              "helpUri": "https://docs.pmd-code.org/snapshot/pmd_rules_java_codestyle.html#methodargumentcouldbefinal",
              "help": {
                "text": "\n            Reports method and constructor parameters that can be made final because they are never reassigned within the body of the method.\n\n            This rule ignores unused parameters so as not to overlap with the rule {% rule java/bestpractices/UnusedFormalParameter %}.\n            It will also ignore the parameters of abstract methods.\n        "
              },
              "properties": {
                "ruleset": "Code Style",
                "priority": 3,
                "tags": [
                  "Code Style"
                ]
              },
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "warning"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "LocalVariableCouldBeFinal",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Local variable 'cmd' could be declared final"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "\nA local variable assigned only once can be declared final.\n        "
              },
              "helpUri": "https://docs.pmd-code.org/snapshot/pmd_rules_java_codestyle.html#localvariablecouldbefinal",
              "help": {
                "text": "\nA local variable assigned only once can be declared final.\n        "
              },
              "properties": {
                "ruleset": "Code Style",
                "priority": 3,
                "tags": [
                  "Code Style"
                ]
              },
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "warning"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "AvoidCatchingGenericException",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Avoid catching Exception in try-catch block"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "\nAvoid catching generic exceptions in try-catch blocks. Catching overly broad exception types makes it difficult\nto understand what can actually go wrong in your code and can hide real problems.\n\n**Why these exceptions should not be caught:**\n\n* **Exception**: This is the base class for all checked exceptions. Catching it means you're handling all possible\n  checked exceptions the same way, which is rarely appropriate and makes error handling less precise.\n\n* **RuntimeException**: These represent programming errors (like logic bugs) that should typically be fixed in\n  code rather than caught and handled. Catching them can hide bugs that should be addressed during development.\n\n* **NullPointerException**: This usually indicates a programming error (accessing null references). Rather than\n  catching it, code should be written to avoid null pointer dereferences through null checks or defensive programming.\n\n* **Throwable**: This is the superclass of all errors and exceptions. Catching it means you're trying to handle\n  both recoverable exceptions and serious errors (like OutOfMemoryError) the same way, which is dangerous.\n\n* **Error**: These represent serious problems that applications should not try to handle (like OutOfMemoryError,\n  StackOverflowError). Catching Error can prevent the JVM from properly terminating when it encounters unrecoverable situations.\n\n**Better approaches:**\n- Catch specific exception types that you can meaningfully handle\n- Use multiple catch blocks for different exception types that require different handling\n- Consider using defensive programming techniques to prevent exceptions rather than catching them\n        "
              },
              "helpUri": "https://docs.pmd-code.org/snapshot/pmd_rules_java_errorprone.html#avoidcatchinggenericexception",
              "help": {
                "text": "\nAvoid catching generic exceptions in try-catch blocks. Catching overly broad exception types makes it difficult\nto understand what can actually go wrong in your code and can hide real problems.\n\n**Why these exceptions should not be caught:**\n\n* **Exception**: This is the base class for all checked exceptions. Catching it means you're handling all possible\n  checked exceptions the same way, which is rarely appropriate and makes error handling less precise.\n\n* **RuntimeException**: These represent programming errors (like logic bugs) that should typically be fixed in\n  code rather than caught and handled. Catching them can hide bugs that should be addressed during development.\n\n* **NullPointerException**: This usually indicates a programming error (accessing null references). Rather than\n  catching it, code should be written to avoid null pointer dereferences through null checks or defensive programming.\n\n* **Throwable**: This is the superclass of all errors and exceptions. Catching it means you're trying to handle\n  both recoverable exceptions and serious errors (like OutOfMemoryError) the same way, which is dangerous.\n\n* **Error**: These represent serious problems that applications should not try to handle (like OutOfMemoryError,\n  StackOverflowError). Catching Error can prevent the JVM from properly terminating when it encounters unrecoverable situations.\n\n**Better approaches:**\n- Catch specific exception types that you can meaningfully handle\n- Use multiple catch blocks for different exception types that require different handling\n- Consider using defensive programming techniques to prevent exceptions rather than catching them\n        "
              },
              "properties": {
                "ruleset": "Error Prone",
                "priority": 3,
                "tags": [
                  "Error Prone"
                ]
              },
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "warning"
              }
            },
